4 days to go.

It's been an interesting week. Exactly one week since oor Nic announced that gyms & yoga/pilates studios can re-open.

I've taken a wee while to digest the news as there are lots of emotions involved & I want to be confident with our return.

I know lots of you are still concerned about the risks involved with studio classes and for this reason we will stay online for a little while longer. 

I have absolutely loved teaching online, I think the accessibility of this platform has suprised us all and it's been amazing to see you all practicing  Pilates more often. Talk about dedication guys! 

I'm working hard to create new content & there's a few new things in the pipeline for your return. I'm excited for the next phase, BUT all in good time amigos.

September Pilates starts this coming Monday and I would absolutely LOVE to see you on the mat...although if you can't make class don't despair...the recording will be sent to you afterwards so you can still get some nutritious movement in ü§∏‍‚ôÄÔ∏èüßò‍‚ôÄÔ∏è

RANT ALERT ‚ö†Ô∏è Social distancing with three children is hard. In fact social distancing with any amount of children is hard! But this week I've found it soul destroying and I've had so many negative experiences that have made me anxious to be out with my children. How "should" we walk in the street? One behind the other? All in a line? Please please if you see a mum like me pushing a buggy with two little ones either side (or any for that matter) don't jump of the pavement and cover your face with a look of terror at my children. Don't frown at them. Don't tut at us and please don't ask me to superglue them to my hip. We are all doing our best. Last time I checked having children wasn't a crime. While you are flapping and trying to keep yourself safe I'm trying to keep my three small children who are too young to wear masks safe. I'm trying to show them that it's ok to be outside despite the fact that everyone looks scary in face coverings. I'm trying to teach them to stand back, keep to one side and not touch anything all while sugar coating the severity of it. Please have some compassion. Please show some kindness. Imagine how scared you feel and times that by 100...because that's how scary it is for the mum you are grimicing at. If you can't be kind then stay at home ‚úåÔ∏è

Drawing for Enjoyment 

Block 18: Online Workshops  Creativity-Connected-Community 

Workshop 2. ”Abstract Collage”  18/6/2020

The second of our online block 18 workshops is formed from our emotional journey throughout lockdown and the connectedness through the FE workshops forum. Taking inspiration from our emotions during Lockdown we produced abstract compositions that meant something to us and we reflected on the struggle for us through a global pandemic. We went for colour, monochrome, simply black and white or a mixture of the three. We produced collages purely using colour to represent our lockdown journey using pattern and shape without text.
Beautiful work expressing some of the highs and lows through the creative process.

During lockdown For Enjoyment CIC has been working away to provide an online supply of live creative workshops. As well as working to supply other organisations we’ve also continued with our regular FE sessions. Drawing for Enjoyment is a Thursday evening institution. The online sessions have been a lifeline in more ways than one. The output from an army of creatives has been incredible and having people joining us from all over Scotland and beyond has reinforced our drive to keep art accessible to everyone. The value of creativity and community under current circumstances is not to be underestimated!
The need to stay connected is extremely important, our values based forum is a great hub for people to come together to do a quintessentially human thing create for the simple pleasure of it. 
Our emphasis is not the production of a masterpiece, nor aiming for a completed piece of work.  Instead, we offer the opportunity to take time out from the stress of the everyday to rediscover the joy of being creative. #workshop #onlineworkshop #lockdown #lockdownworkshops #covid19 #creativity #connected #community #collage #abstract #forenjoyment #drawingforenjoyment #2nd #socialimpact #collage #collageart #collageartist

A little toy shop in Upton caught my eye. Great name for a toy shop. It was nice to see that the guard was wearing his mask.

Please take the time to read this message.

This picture is iconic of our time. From a fantastic old school toy shop in Upton - a child's dream place. For me, this pandemic has impacted children alot more than many will know. What a time we live in - The Guarded by saviors in masks. 

Many children have missed out on so much. From 
swinging on swings or sliding down slides. Tagging and chasing friends, trading and sharing. Buying a new toy from a shop and having sleepovers. A friendly hug, handshake or pat on the back. Talking with friends and teachers and aunties and uncles. 

For some children, the time has been lonely and scary with each day carrying uncertainty. Some have suffered greatly from families in desperate need of guidance and support. Some children, its heartbraking to say, will have spent lockdown with undeserving parents. It is these children who will be affected greatly for years to come.

However, I think it's safe to say that many parents have realised, that there isn't much that can replace the gift of love a parent can give. Many parents have spent time education, caring, working, supporting in a time when those normal duties have become so much more difficult. I know the NHS and key workers have worked valiantly through this. But, parents don't forget, you are heroes too.

Throwing it back to when #stayhome , #curfews and #lockdowns started. 

My ambivert-ly introverted self was quite pleased to stay indoors and also avoid sunlight triggered migraines. 

But then I realized, before, my human interaction always occurred. Be it at night running errands or attending shows and movies, I still interacted with people. This lockdown was something else. And so my interaction with people via my written word increased online. With the personal accounts deactivated I might add. I even finally opened my IG poetry page. @thedivinebanditpoet just so I could share much more often and easily. 

With all this work done, typing, editing and posting etc. My hands, fingers and wrists included have raised a complaint. And so even my beloved chatting instead of calls is now a problem. I am now forced to choose when to type and the importance of what I am about to type. It also means I have developed regular resting time when typing to manage the RSI pain. This gets worse towards the evening as it gets cold.  I had never thought anything would ever stop me writing. Before, I have woken up to write, written at 2 am and other ungodly hours, in restaurants waiting for people who say they are 5 minutes away for 2 hours etc. Anytime I have wanted to, I could write and now this has come to be, even if for a short while. 

However I do also realize that keeping the words I usually write inside would probably hurt more than my wrists do as I type this out. So be it by using voice command (if the accent will even have the right words typed out üòÇüòÇ) or sending recordings to someone to type them out üòÖ.
Even if my fingers #lockdown and my wrists have a #curfew 
Rest assured my words won't #stayhome

node.text:
God works in mysterious ways.
Isaiah 55:8-9
“For my thoughts are not your thoughts,
 neither are your ways my ways,”
declares the Lord.
“As the heavens are higher than the earth,
 so are my ways higher than your ways
  and my thoughts than your thoughts.
.
Sometimes you feel like God has forsaken you, you feel alone. But when it feels that way or when you're going through your darkest periods, trust that God is just setting things up for your success. Walking you through the valley of the shadow of death to deliver you to the light.
.
No matter how dark and sad life feels, no matter what situations are going on around you, trust that God is working for your good, and that he's preparing amazing plans for your salvation and to deliver you.
.
Joseph's story starts in Genesis 37 if you'd like to read it.
